Starlink Solution
-----------------

That Sharp Tech episode was recorded last week because I am currently somew=
here in the far reaches of Canada, four hours north of the U.S. border, and=
 I wasn=E2=80=99t sure if I would be able to record Sharp Tech given the la=
ck of Internet. After all, I am sitting on a houseboat that is a 45-minute =
speedboat ride from the nearest dock, which itself is 45 minutes away from =
the nearest town, which itself only has 1,200 people.

The reason I ended up here was a note from one of my high school buddies ea=
rlier this year, who told me that a whole bunch of my friends from high sch=
ool were coming to Canada on a fishing trip; moreover, this fishing trip wo=
uldn=E2=80=99t be like the ones I dreaded in my youth, where we packed ever=
ything in and slept on the ground, but rather in said houseboat, which had =
one more bed available. Was I interested?

To be perfectly honest, was I interested in fishing? Not really; I get the =
allure, but don=E2=80=99t have nearly the patience. However, was I interest=
ed in hanging out with old buddies, drinking beer, eating fresh fish, playi=
ng cards, and breaking out some board games? Absolutely!

There was just one problem: the week they had reserved the houseboat was, w=
ell, this week, which was one week before the unmovable Stratechery summer =
break; as much as I might prefer to work the first week of July, I know tha=
t none of my American subscribers are willing to read then, and I just didn=
=E2=80=99t feel good about taking a two week break.

There was, though, a potential solution: Starlink. What if I could work in =
the mornings and hang out in the evenings? After all, I was there to hang o=
ut, not to fish.

I bought the standard $599 satellite receiver using Starlink=E2=80=99s one-=
page ordering form; while the simplicity was nice, I actually found it a de=
triment, as it wasn=E2=80=99t clear to me that there were different service=
 plans available. The order form defaulted to the residential offering, whi=
ch locks service to the address you have the satellite receiver delivered t=
o; I needed the regional roaming plan, which covers all of North America (I=
 found out about the distinction by chance in the context of a group chat a=
 few days before I left, and quickly upgraded).

From what I understand the increase in service plan options is a big change=
 from Starlink=E2=80=99s early days, and one that makes a lot of sense give=
n that bandwidth is a scarce resource. The options available to me with my =
standard satellite receiver were as follows (there is also a high performan=
ce satellite receiver for $2,500 that provides better weather resistance an=
d better visibility to satellites for places with unavoidable obstructions)=
:

Service Level Priority Cap Location Price/month Standard =E2=80=94 One $120=
 Standard $2/GB Continent $150 Standard $2/GB World $200 Priority 1TB One $=
250 Priority 2TB One $500 Priority 6TB One $1,500 Priority 50GB World $250 =
Priority 1TB World $1,000 Priority 5TB World $5,000

For clarity=E2=80=99s sake, you can proactively buy priority data access on=
 the roaming standard plans, which is priced on a per-GB basis; the other p=
riority plans include a set allotment of data. All plans are cancellable im=
mediately.

For my part I=E2=80=99ve been on location two-and-a-half days as I write th=
is; we have consumed 64GB of data, and that=E2=80=99s without any streaming=
 video (that I know of, anyways). I=E2=80=99ve also recorded one podcast wi=
th video (yesterday=E2=80=99s Dithering ( https://dithering.fm/ ) ), and ha=
ven=E2=80=99t felt any need to buy priority data. That, though, isn=E2=80=
=99t a surprise: remember, I just explained how remote my location is, whic=
h is to say that I am probably not competing with very many people for acce=
ss to the satellites passing by overhead; priority plans would be much more=
 important were I in a more densely populated area =E2=80=94 at least if th=
at area had a lot of Starlinks.

I=E2=80=99m jumping ahead, though; I have pictures!

Starlink Experience
-------------------

First off, I setup the Starlink =E2=80=94 which consisted of nothing more t=
han attaching the satellite receiver to its base, connecting the cable betw=
een the receiver and router, and plugging in the router =E2=80=94 on top of=
 the houseboat:

This is basically the ideal Starlink use case; there are no obstructions an=
d, perhaps unsurprisingly =E2=80=94 but in defiance of the skepticism that =
led me to record Sharp Tech last week =E2=80=94 performance has been excell=
ent.

I usually get between 150-200 Mbps down and 10~25 Mbps up with ping times o=
f 100~200ms:

Sometimes, though, the connection speed would dramatically drop; this scree=
nshot was taken just a few minutes after the one above, with my laptop lite=
rally next to the Starlink router:

Here is the router on top of a freezer (we usually had it tucked in behind =
it):

The experience was, frankly, incredible in the way the best technologies ar=
e, which is to say you didn=E2=80=99t even notice it. Whereas previously be=
ing on this trip meant having no access to the outside world, now the Inter=
net just worked, and it worked at a speed and reliability that was perfectl=
y fine: as I noted above, I worked as normal, including recording a podcast=
 with video, and never even noticed the speed except for the occasional slo=
w upload (and even then it wasn=E2=80=99t much worse than cable Internet).

In short, there is no question that Starlink dramatically expands the numbe=
r of locations that are viable for those who rely on Internet connectivity =
for their life or job, but its not a panacea: Starlink still needs electric=
ity, and that means a generator:

Starlink wasn=E2=80=99t the only reason to have a generator; I noted the fr=
eezer above, and the houseboat also had a refrigerator and electrical outle=
ts generally (the lights were battery powered). Still, this part of the exp=
erience wasn=E2=80=99t great: the generator was loud, even though we moved =
it as far away from the boat as we could manage; it also relied on gasoline=
, which had to be carried in, and which obviously isn=E2=80=99t great for t=
he environment. Moreover, sometimes it ran out of gas:

When this happened =E2=80=94 or when we shut down the generator for the nig=
ht, or when everyone left to go fishing =E2=80=94 there was no more Interne=
t. Refilling and restarting the generator usually brought things back =E2=
=80=94 it only took a couple of minutes for Starlink to re-orient itself an=
d lock on to a satellite =E2=80=94 but sometimes the receiver would fail to=
 reboot and would have to be power-cycled. That seems like a bit of a bug, =
but the bigger takeaway is that while Internet may seem essential, there ar=
e a lot of other things lower down on Maslow=E2=80=99s hierarchy of needs, =
and when it comes to technology, energy is the base layer.

And, of course, it=E2=80=99s fair to question how much better the Internet =
makes things, at least in the context of a fishing trip. Obviously it was t=
he price of my attendance, so that I could write these Updates, but I did f=
eel like a bit of a usurper to the spirit of the whole expedition: my best-=
friend-from-high-school=E2=80=99s dad is on his 78th Canada fishing trip; t=
his is the first time he has been connected to the outside world (he told m=
e the story of missing the end of the USSR while in Canada), and I wonder i=
f he is a bit bummed that, for the first time, there are distractions from =
filleting fish, playing bridge, or simply hanging out. No, I=E2=80=99m not =
a full-on Luddite, but it=E2=80=99s fair to wonder if the Internet cost us =
something years ago, and if Starlink costs us the chance to even experience=
 what the world used to be like, if only for a week.

Starlink Implications
---------------------

This Update is, to be clear, about my experience using Starlink, and on bal=
ance, I am extremely impressed. There are a lot of other issues to think ab=
out, though, including how SpaceX makes Starlink possible on a technical le=
vel (faster speeds and lower latencies are achieved using much lower satell=
ites, which means you need many more satellites to cover the globe effectiv=
ely, which is viable if you have dramatically lower launch costs) and how S=
tarlink is essential to SpaceX=E2=80=99s economics (communications remains =
the single most compelling way to earn money in space, and SpaceX needs a w=
ay to use up all of its launch capacity that doesn=E2=80=99t entail cutting=
 prices to the extent it can=E2=80=99t make enough money to invest in highe=
r capacity rockets).

There are also questions about the effect on astronomy ( https://www.astron=
omy.com/space-exploration/starlink-satellite-streaks-how-big-of-a-problem-a=
re-they/ ) , potential problems in terms of space debris and overcrowding (=
both of which may be overstated ( https://caseyhandmer.wordpress.com/2019/1=
0/25/space-debris-probably-not-coming-to-a-backyard-near-you/ ) ), and Star=
link=E2=80=99s military applications ( https://www.livescience.com/china-pl=
ans-ways-destroy-starlink ). The fact that these are even issues to be rais=
ed, though, speaks to what a big deal Starlink potentially is.

When it comes to consumer applications, though, I=E2=80=99m a bit more rese=
rved. Obviously my current use case is incredible, and that extends to rura=
l or water-based applications everywhere: having not just the Internet ever=
ywhere, but the Internet everywhere at broadband speeds and reasonable pric=
es is a game-changer. At a minimum I think that any further subsidies for r=
ural broadband is a waste of money; just subsidize Starlinks.

By the same token, though, it=E2=80=99s not clear why anyone with cable bro=
adband would ever want to switch, much less fiber. Starlink may be competit=
ive with ADSL, but only if you have a mounting point with an unencumbered v=
iew of the sky. The latency in particular, while still spectacular as compa=
red to previous satellite options, will never be as good =E2=80=94 but then=
 again, my experience was more than good enough for video calling, and that=
 may be good enough for consumers who don=E2=80=99t play video games.

What could potentially get better is the price: Starlink has plans to launc=
h tens of thousand of more satellites, which will provide bandwidth that, i=
n the short term, will alleviate the need for priority access and, in the l=
ong run, will need to be filled, probably by offering lower priced service.=
 Maybe one day Starlink will get sued by the FTC for trying to pay for that=
 capacity with dark patterns!

